Chesney also wrote and produced a documentary for ESPN The Boys Of Fall.

description.plain:
Co-written by Chesney, Shane McAnally, and Josh Osborne, “Wild Child” was released in February, 2015, as the third single off Chesney’s 2014 album The Big Revival.

The song features Grace Potter’s vocals – the two previously collaborated on “You and Tequila” and “El Cerrito Place”.

Speaking about the song, Chesney told Billboard

 Over the last several years, it seems like anytime anybody sings about a woman, she’s in cutoff jeans, drinking and on a tailgate — they objectify the hell out of them! […] But I’m at a point where I want to say something different about women.

description.plain:
In “All the Pretty Girls,” Chesney sings about young love and the summer romance we all wish we had.

The song peaked at #7 on Billboard’s “Hot Country Songs” chart and at #63 on the “Hot 100” chart.

Chesney held a contest, open to students from Nashville’s Belmont University and Middle Tennessee State University in Murfreesboro, to direct the music video to the single. Speaking about the contest, Chesney said:

You live it, dream it, film it. Then send it to us. I’m looking for a video that captures what this song is really about, so I’m going to the source. Have some fun with it, and show us what you’ve got.

The winners, Belmont students Jessica Martinez and William Renner, received a $5,000 scholarship in addition to their winning video being uploaded to VEVO and Spotify.

description.plain: Chesney explained the song’s meaning: “‘Come Over’” is about two people who are as broken as their relationship is, when they realize deep down that their time together has probably ran its course, but they aren’t really ready to emotionally or physically move on to something else,“ he said. "They keep going back to each other because it’s familiar. It’s about emotionally feeling wanted in a moment, but it feels impossible to let anybody else fill that void. It’s a really sexy song with lyrics that are incredibly universal.”

songs.title: The Boys Of Fall

description.plain:
“Boys of Fall” was released in July 2010 as the first single off of Hemingway’s Whiskey, Kenny Chesney’s 12th studio album. “Boys of Fall” hit number one on the Billboard Hot 100 Country Songs chart on October 9th and remained for the following week.

Kenny wrote the song about his hometown: Corryton, Tennessee.

Where I come from, there are a few things that really matter: God, family, friends and sports-especially football. And not just college or professional football. High school football.

For the song’s music video, Kenny shot footage of his friend Sean Payton, coach of the New Orleans Saints, at Kenny’s alma mater Gibbs High School. After filming began, Kenny decided to expand the video into a documentary with the same name, Boys of Fall.

Kenny played as a wide receiver for his high school football team, the Gibbs Eagles. With “Boys of Fall”, Kenny wanted to also show the impact playing football had on him:

I honestly believe that if I’d not played high school football, I wouldn’t be where I am today. The lessons you learn, the values you absorb, the power of teamwork: When you’re playing ball, it’s what you do; when you get into the world, it’s the way you apply yourself to life.

The video also features scenes from other notable high school programs, such as Celina, Texas (which has eight state titles, tied for most in the state).

Written by Craig Wiseman and Steve McEwan, Kenny Chesney released “Summertime” in April, 2006. The lyrics are a collection of memories from the singer’s youth.

Of penning the lyrics, Wiseman told The Boot:

It was that first night when it stays warm, and you can smell the grass growing. I walked outside and was like, ‘Man … summertime! Smell that!’ It was that first warm night of summer. It was great.

Though the lyrics are similar to “summertime, and the livin’s easy,” this song is not to be confused with “Doin' Time” by Sublime.

description.plain:
The fourth single from Chesney’s The Big Revival, the song is an anthem designed to cast negative thoughts and emotions to the side, and enjoy the sunshine while it lasts, saving the “heartbreak” for a day when he’s not in such a good mood.

The track reached number 54 on the US Billboard charts, and featured a video of Chesney enjoying picturesque American country side, and fishing his troubles away.

songs.full_title: Better As A Memory by Kenny Chesney
songs.title: Better As A Memory

description.plain:
“Better As A Memory” served as the fourth and final single off of Chesneys' 2008 album “Just Who I Am: Poets & Pirates.” The ballad ended up reaching the number one spot on the Billboard Hot Country Songs chart.

Lyrically, the song describes a man talking to his girlfriend about their impending breakup. He explains to her that she shouldn’t be getting too involved with him, telling her that he is “better as a memory than as [her] man.” He is quick to assure her though that one day she will indeed find the right man, she’s not the issue in this relationship, he is.

Critics ended up loving the song, highly regarded Nashville critic Robert K Oermann said, “[‘Better as a Memory’] could be the performance of [Chesney’s] life, [and] perhaps his career.” Others saying his vocals were “spot on”

songs.full_title: Pirate Song by Kenny Chesney
songs.title: Pirate Song

description.plain:
From Kenny’s Instagram:
“Pirate Song is out today and it’s a love song to everything the islands have always been: freedom, time slowing down, being calm and at sea. Even when my friends and people I knew were coming through my house after the storms came through, I knew the essence of what those islands are couldn’t be extinguished inside them.
#SONGSFORTHESAINTS isn’t about the destruction and devastation as much as it is the beauty of life in the islands and the way its people create a life that is their own.
Anyone who’s got a job, a schedule, a list of responsibilities and people to answer to understands that yearning to be free. This song is about being unplugged, off the grid, sailing where the boat takes you and letting the cares drift away. It’s never that easy, but I love that line about Saint Christopher on a silver chain, say a prayer, and sail away… because it is also that easy if you’ll just surrender.

That’s why when they asked me to pick a song to send out early, I picked this one. It’s everything I wish for everyone in @noshoesnation: the ability to let go and melt into the stillness. We all want to be pirates in some way or another. It’s such a romantic idea, so rock & roll, and it’s also so much more… and less."

songs.full_title: El Cerrito Place by Kenny Chesney
songs.title: El Cerrito Place

description.plain:
“El Cerrito Place” is the third single to be released off of Kenny’s album Welcome To The Fishbowl. The song was originally sung by Charlie Robinson, Kenny said that he wanted to cover it because he could relate to it.

The song is a haunting ballad that describes a man that is longing for his past lover that lives in the El Cerrito Place Apartments at the foot of the Hollywood Hills in California. The man has decided to travel back to where she lives in order to try and find her to make her his again. The narrator longs to find his ex-lover again, even though he spends days trying to find her.

Of the song, Kenny said:

It’s about wanting something that’s obviously not there … this searching that we all have for love and lust, and someone that’s not in your life anymore. It talks about all of the measures that we go through to feel loved and to get that certain thing back that’s just driving you crazy.

Kenny continued by adding that it shows a very strong human characteristic, insanity. The man in the song is obsessed with finding his lover, which Kenny referred to as insanity. Humans very rarely view obsession as a form as insanity, but there is a very thin line between obsession and insanity, and the narrator may have just crossed the line. Kenny finished by saying: “There’s searching and longing that all of us have inside. I’ve felt every bit of emotion that the character in that song deals with.”
